title: Part 6
content:
Part 6

IN THE EVENING, after finishing their supply retrieval, Horikita and the others arrived at G8 around 5:25 p.m. This arrival time was a result of their constant wariness of an ambush, which had them keep the option of taking the route south from E6 to E8 open until the last possible moment. And just as they had five minutes prior, they received a report that the students from Class B and the Class C/D alliance were keeping their distance from G8.

"I wonder what happened to the eight GPS signals that went to retrieve supplies at G9?"

The instructions she'd been emphasizing over and over were confirmed by Matsushita through her VIP, Wang.

"It seems that at 5:25, they were all observed moving back toward H10."

"What the hell? So Ryuuen didn't make a move after all, even though they were up against a small group?"

They assumed that if one side moved, the other would move to intercept, but it didn't lead to a confrontation. As a result, the group of eight students from Class C and Class D succeeded in retrieving the supplies without any trouble.

"It can't be helped. No one could have predicted that Koenji-kun would take down nine people."

"...Yeah, I guess. But one thing's for sure, he wasn't fightin' for us. He even casually dropped by the beach and retired afterward. This ain't a game."

Horikita nodded once in agreement with Sudou's words. Koenji accidentally entered a state of combat with ten students from Class B who moved to retrieve supplies and he defeated nine of them. All nine people he took out were guards; the VIP wasn't among the defeated students. However, coordination between the analyst and the VIP and the VIP and the commander, was essential for accurately retrieving supplies. Immediately after learning of the battle, Horikita had them use tactics to identify the individuals, confirming that the only student who escaped was Morofuji Rika and that her role was the VIP.

"In any case, we need to focus on ourselves rather than the other classes right now. I don't think they'll attack us with just those eight people nearby, but tell everyone to remain vigilant."

Since they were only ten or fifteen minutes away in a straight line, the possibility that they would attack using individual GPS shutdowns was not, for the time being, zero. That was why she communicated to Matsushita to keep watch without letting her guard down.

It was fifteen minutes later that Horikita, unable to fully shake her tension, finally felt a sense of relief.

After three GPS updates, the Class C students who'd been staying north of G9 finished retrieving their supplies and moved southeast. It was when she finished confirming that they were about to rendezvous with their allies in their designated waiting area, just before passing slightly through G10 and on to H10. There were only twenty minutes left. It was a distance that neither Class B nor the Class C/D alliance could possibly cover.

"Good work, everyone—we can get some proper rest around here today."

At her voice, her classmates all lowered their weapons at once and took their tents out of their backpacks. Because the trees were dense, they could not pitch their tents together, so each of them began to work separately.

It was just then.

"Uwah!"

A loud scream suddenly came from one of the boys, Hondou.

Horikita's heart skipped a beat for a moment, but the cause of the scream was immediately clear.

It was because a tree branch had pierced his tent, opening up a small hole.

"Damn, there's seriously no space to pitch a tent here."

"It can't be helped. This is the best position if we're to prepare for tomorrow. Be careful as you work."

In about five minutes, Horikita finished setting up her own sleeping quarters and stretched once.

"This is rough—"

Although they hadn't engaged in combat, they were about to face the third night with food constantly scarce and not enough water. Her body was already in a state where it was beginning to show signs of its limit. It was a harshness unlike that of any uninhabited island exam from the past two years.

A short distance away, Horikita spotted Karuizawa and two other girls who'd just finished their work and recalled what she wanted to talk about during the day if she had time. She approached them.

"Do you have a minute?"

"Hm? What's up, Horikita-san?"

Since she had even less stamina than Horikita, the signs of her fatigue were pronounced, but she put on a smile and looked at Horikita.

"There's something I want to ask you... but it's difficult to talk about here—"

She excused herself to Shinohara and Onodera, who were near Karuizawa and they moved to a spot a short distance away.

"Something you want to talk to me about? It's something you don't want overheard, right?"

"Yes, well, a little—"

As a cool breeze gently enveloped the two of them, Horikita took off her goggles as if to catch her breath.

The time was almost 6:00. As a rule, they had to keep them on until the exam ended, but she judged that it wouldn't matter anymore. Seeing this, Karuizawa also took off her goggles.

"It's pretty hot keeping these goggles on, isn't it?"

Karuizawa let out a breath and relaxed into the pleasant breeze.

"Ask me anything. We're friends, aren't we?"

Without even looking at Horikita, who'd been unable to broach the subject, she asked and Horikita steeled her resolve.

"It's about Class C and D. In the end, we've come to the evening of the third day without the GPS signals of either class decreasing significantly all day. It's a situation where there's no doubt that the two classes have joined hands."

"Yeah, there's no mistake about that. It's easy for losing classes to team up."

This much had been talked about all over the class from last night until now.

It wasn't something that required a private conversation between the two of them.

If that were the case, she immediately understood that Horikita wanted to take it one step further.

"What's bothering me is when the two classes decided to team up. We couldn't make contact with other classes when the special exam details were announced and their starting positions were far apart, with our class in between."

Since communication between commanders was also impossible, there was definitely no contact.

"Class D is a special class. They might have felt sympathy seeing Class C in a wounded state. However, that doesn't mean it's easy to suddenly accept a half-destroyed enemy. It shouldn't have been easy to form an alliance without some prior arrangement..."

"Yeah. Hirata-kun and the others said the same thing. They were speculating about all sorts of things, like maybe he not only threw the match but also gave them Private Points."

Karuizawa spoke while reminiscing and while Horikita agreed, she voiced another possibility.

"Right after he left the class, he and Ichinose-san became close... well, 'close' might be the wrong word, but I've sensed that they've been closing the distance between them."

The opening ceremony when he left the class. That day, Ayanokouji already met with Ichinose in addition to the Class C students after school. Perhaps their cooperation had been in motion beneath the surface since then.

Wanting confirmation on that point, Horikita replied to Karuizawa.

"I see... yeah, I think so too. In fact, I'm sure of it."

"So you think the same."

"Yeah. The relationship between Class C and D has definitely gotten deeper than before."

Karuizawa nodded firmly. In response, Horikita made a mental note that she might need to reconsider the future.

"Um... you kinda dodged this the other day, but can I ask you something a little more personal?"

"Hm, I dodged something? What are you talking about?"

"Even though you're enemies now, do you like Ayanokouji-kun, Horikita-san?"

"Huh? Wh-when you said 'more personal,' you meant that?"

"It's pretty important to me."

"I-I already told you, I've never been in love with anyone, have I not?"

"But you're flustered."

"When someone asks you a question like whether you like someone or not, it's only natural to get flustered."

Placing both hands behind her back along with her goggles, Horikita averted her gaze.

"Then do you like Sudou-kun?"

"Of course not. He's a dependable classmate."

"See? You answered instantly. And it was a similar question."

With a grin, Karuizawa pointed at Horikita as she made her point.

"That's—"

It was true; when it came to Ayanokouji, her mind would freeze for a moment and she couldn't think straight.

She felt it for some time.

It wasn't as if she'd never questioned it.

And yet, she still hadn't found the right answer for her own feelings.

"If you're holding back because of me, you don't have to. I don't think it's a bad thing to like the same person... besides..."

For a moment, the smile vanished from Karuizawa's face, replaced by a shadow.

"Besides... what?"

She couldn't help but ask.

"It's not just me and you who like Ayanokouji-kun, Horikita-san. Ichinose-san does too."

"...She does...? No, I'm not that surprised, but... is that true?"

"It's true. And I think their relationship is probably more than you imagine, Horikita-san."

"You mean... they're dating?"

For a moment, she wondered if that might be one of the reasons they had formed an alliance.

But Karuizawa shook her head and continued quietly.

"Um, I don't think so... but it's something close to that, I guess."

"I'm sorry, I don't quite understand what you mean—"

Just as she started to ask for more details, noisy voices came from the direction of the campsite.

Karuizawa in front of her also sensed the faint disturbance and their eyes met.

Just as it seemed to have gone quiet for a moment, the noisy voices returned.

This time, they didn't die down and with the passage of time, the clamor grew twice as loud.

Mixed in with those voices, the sound of a projectile flying could be faintly heard.

A dry sound echoed repeatedly.

"Is someone shooting? Am I imagining things?"

That was the question. However, the dry sounds continued to come from the direction of the tents.

"...There's no mistaking it."

The sound of someone firing a paintball gun rang out.

During the exam, they'd fired paintballs for practice several times, so it was by no means an unusual sound.

Even so, a sense of unease filled her.

The time on her watch showed it was just past 5:57 PM.

Strictly speaking, it was a time when the exam was not yet over.

But it was impossible.

She received a report that all eight GPS signals remaining nearby were on their way back to the enemy's main force. From that point, even if they aimed for Class A, there was no way a normal person could've made it in time.

"Let's go back."

The two of them ran toward the direction of the sound.

She hoped it was just a shot fired on accident, or playing around.

Horikita strongly wished for that, but upon returning near the tent, she noticed the disaster.

Ijuuin, standing stunned nearby, noticed Horikita's presence and turned around.

"Ugh... I was shot!"

Ijuuin clutched his abdomen, where a paintball splattered and the alarm on his watch was ringing. And as she looked around, between the erected tents, she caught sight of Mori with a splash of paint across her back.

"How many enemies!?"

"I-I don't know. Someone suddenly started shooting from the woods... a-and, but Sudou and the others went chasing after them that way!"

In the direction he pointed, several students were still running, weapons in hand.

She thought about returning to the tent to retrieve her weapon, but decided it was better to rush over even a second sooner, Horikita immediately followed after the students.

While readjusting her goggles, she took the handgun from the holster on her leg that she hadn't removed and scanned for the unseen allies and enemies.

Ahead, the sound of gunfire continued, two, three times.

She'd fired the handgun several times in practice, but even so, she'd yet to fire a single shot in actual combat.

It was the same for her allies fighting back ahead of her, who'd been caught completely by surprise. A sense of urgency grew within her, thinking that it was no different from when Class C was ambushed.

"Where... where are you...?!"

If there were multiple enemies, she felt she should've spotted at least one, but she saw no one other than her classmates. Kicking up dirt and treading on leaves, Horikita spotted a human silhouette ahead and raised her gun.

But it was an ally, not an enemy. She found Onodera sitting down, having been shot in the back. Noticing the footsteps, Onodera turned around, her expression regretful, but she immediately pointed to the northeast.

"Don't worry about me—that way!"

"Thank you!"

She passed by her and rushed ahead, gun raised. Where her vision opened up slightly, she saw several students continuously firing their paintball guns toward a single point.

"Corner him! This way!"

"He went that way!"

Lost amidst those voices, Horikita tried to grasp the situation and called out to Miyamoto, who was holding a shotgun.

"The enemy? How many?"

"It's Ayanokouji! Ayanokouji! He came barging in here all on his own!"

"...!"

At that moment, several classmates moved in from the left and right, trying to circle around behind a large tree.

"So he's over there...?"

Miyamoto nodded. Even Horikita, who'd just arrived, could see at a glance that Ayanokouji was completely surrounded and in an inescapable situation. He'd already been cornered.

There was no way for him to hide from the paintballs fired by the students surrounding the large tree.

Not only were Horikita and Miyamoto in front of him, but there were also male and female guards to his left, right and rear. It was truly a hopeless situation.

To attack alone and infiltrate the Class A campsite was far too reckless.

Although he'd taken down several guards, she wondered if it was worth the value of a student like Ayanokouji.

Horikita felt a sense of doubt at an action so disproportionate to the risk, but there wasn't enough time to find an answer.

Another three or four seconds—

And with that, this commotion would come to an end.

Before his classmates could complete their encirclement, Ayanokouji moved.

He took half a step forward from behind the large tree, aimed only at Ike and moved to raise his weapon.

Was his intention to take at least one person down with him if he was going to be defeated?

However, just a fraction of a second faster, the Class A students placed their fingers on the trigger.

"Fire—!!"

Hondou shouted as if giving a command; the situation was perfectly set up for a 100% elimination.

But—

It was then that Horikita realized it. She realized what Ayanokouji's aim was and why he was able to charge in all by himself.

"No! Don't shoot!"

Almost at the same time as the sound of someone's gunshot, Horikita screamed.

However, four of the students who had their weapons ready already finished pulling the trigger.

Paintballs hit Ayanokouji's right hand, right foot and the area near his side one after another, just as he was about to shoot them. The alarm blaring from his watch clearly indicated he was out.

"I did it! I did it! I'm the one who took down Ayanokouji! Serves you right, Ayanokouji!"

Ike, who hadn't heard the voice telling them to stop, jumped for joy.

The casualties were three people: Ijuuin, Onodera and Mori. It was a one-for-three trade, but it was a different story when the opponent was Ayanokouji. The students must have even thought they'd come out ahead by defeating the leader.

In a situation where it wouldn't have been strange to be celebrating, Horikita squeezed her eyes shut.

"It's no use... He isn't out..."

"Huh? I'm tellin' ya, they were clear hits! His watch is goin' off and everything!"

The classmates exchanged high-fives, unable to contain their excitement.

But the one who was calmer and more composed than anyone was the man who should have been out.

"My bad, Ike. It looks like you're the ones who are out, not me."

"What the hell is that...?! I don't get i—"

"...It's six o'clock. It's already past six o'clock."

The watch Horikita confirmed by bending her left arm had just passed 6:00:32.

"Huh...? Wha...?"

"The moment it turns 6:00 p.m., that day's test ends. All subsequent eliminations are rendered invalid and the student who fired the shot to take someone down is eliminated instead—that was the rule, wasn't it, Horikita?"

A solo attack, aimed at a moment when their guards were down.

The anger of having their comrades taken out and the perfect opportunity to defeat a traitor.

The students, driven by impulse, had completely forgotten about the current time.

If it was even one second past 6:00 p.m., the elimination was invalid. The signal emitted from Ayanokouji's watch clearly recorded him as safe.

"If you charge into the enemy camp alone, you won't get away unscathed. You deliberately used that, didn't you..."

"That's right. My bad."

Ayanokouji answered and glanced at Horikita for just a moment, but immediately looked away.

Sometime after 7:00 p.m., the school staff arrived and supplied Ayanokouji with a new tracksuit, after which the four students who fired and hit him outside of test hours retired by self-reporting.

The result of one person charging in alone was that he forced a mistake from his opponent and got as many as seven students eliminated.

While the commotion still continued, Ayanokouji silently began to set up his tent.

"H-Hey, what the hell are you doin' settin' up a tent here?!"

"I was under the impression I was free to set it up anywhere, but am I being a nuisance?"

"Of course you are!"

"That's no good, Hondou-kun. It's better not to keep Ayanokouji-kun at a distance."

"Huh? So what're you sayin', Hirata? That we should sleep with the enemy?"

"Fighting outside of hours is forbidden and if Ayanokouji-kun cheats, he'll be retired. What I'm trying to say is that if we keep Ayanokouji-kun at a distance, it will be easier for him to escape. Besides, at nine o'clock tomorrow morning, he absolutely has to start from the same area as us."

"O-Oh, right. So we can just blast him with paintballs when morning comes...!"

"Because you understood that, you decided to set up your tent here too, didn't you, Ayanokouji-kun?"

"Even if I were to keep my distance and set up camp somewhere else as if to escape now, it's obvious you'd just come to surround me in the morning anyway. It's better if we both don't waste our energy."

"Hey, you know... I don't think you realize you're in the enemy's cage, do you...?"

Next to Hondou, Shinohara, who'd been glaring with resentment over Ike being eliminated, grumbled this.

"That might be true."

Answering matter-of-factly without denying it, Ayanokouji went inside the tent he'd pitched.

Horikita was unable to say a single word and could only stare, dumbfounded.
